    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>NO RELIEF IN IRISH INFLATION</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Brian Lavery</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Lavery, Brian</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Irish inflation rate remained at 6.2 percent in August, highest in European Union; government says rate will moderate by end of year, but Irish economists predict that worldwide increase in oil prices will push inflation up to 7 percent within next few months; three of Ireland's largest trade unions call for renegotiation of national wage agreement put in place when inflation ran at 2.5 percent (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>The inflation rate in Ireland remained at 6.2 percent in August, the highest in the European Union, according to figures released by the Central Statistics Office. The government said the rate would moderate by the end of the year, but Irish economists predicted that the worldwide increase in oil prices would push inflation up to 7 percent within the next few months. In response to the figures, three of Ireland's largest trade unions called for a renegotiation of the national wage agreement put in place when inflation ran at 2.5 percent.</p>
        <p>Brian Lavery</p>
      </block>
